Weather and Morel mushroom observations

Ill start by loading the morel observations into R. To review, I started with a dataset of about 1800 observations of morel mushrooms in the United States that were submitted to the website iNaturalist. I chose only those observations for which the location was certain to within a kilometer. In my last notebook, I explained how I got historical weather data from the Open Meteo API. I chose a random sample of the observations, for which the API returned information about the air temperature, soil temperature, humidity, and precipitation in the two weeks preceding the observation.

Because I dont have data for the periods when morels were NOT observed, I wont try to identify the factors that predict morel emergence. Rather, my goal is to explore the distribution of climate variables before the morels pop up to get and idea of what conditions are sufficient to give the woods explorer a chance of finding morels.

morel_data <- read.csv("morchella_observations_and_weather_sample.csv")

The weather data are stored as JSON objects. I wrote a function to parse the data into tibbles. Before transforming the weather data, Ill also deal with missing data. The API I used returned None if no data was available for a particular request. Fortunately in this case none of the rows had missing data.

convert_from_json <- function(json){
  tmp <- fromJSON(json, simplifyDataFrame = TRUE)
  tmp <- as_tibble(tmp, name_repair="minimal")
  return (tmp)
}
morel_data_filtered <- morel_data %>%
  filter(!str_detect(daily,"None")) %>%
  filter(!str_detect(hourly,"None"))
daily_data <-
  mapply(convert_from_json, morel_data_filtered$daily, SIMPLIFY = FALSE)

hourly_data <-
  mapply(convert_from_json, morel_data_filtered$hourly, SIMPLIFY = FALSE)

Very nice!

I might want to work with the data as dates and date-times rather than strings, so Ill need to convert the data types. Im also going to add a column called t_minus, which will allow me to order the findings by time without messing with confusing date/time syntax. I found selecting values from a data frame nested in another data frame a little confusing. Although Im sure there are better ways to do this, I eventually worked this out:

convert_tibble <- function(tibble,format){
  mutate(tibble, time = parse_date_time(time,format))
  mutate(tibble, t_minus=c((length(time)-1):0))
}

daily_data <- daily_data %>%
  lapply(convert_tibble,"ymd")


hourly_data <- hourly_data %>%
  lapply(convert_tibble,"ymdHM")

Now Ill accumulate the data into a single data frame, which makes it easier to work with. Each observation will be tagged with an ID

convert_to_dataframe <- function(dataset){
  dataset <- enframe(dataset)
  dataset['id'] <- c(1:length(dataset$value))
  dataset <- unnest(dataset, cols=c(value)) 
  return(dataset)
}

daily_data <- convert_to_dataframe(daily_data)
hourly_data <- convert_to_dataframe(hourly_data)

Ill start with the daily data, which covers only precipitation. In particular, Im curious whether some amount of precipitation is necessary for morels to start fruiting and continue maturing. Once they start fruiting, morels take 10-15 days to reach maturity (from the work of the great mycologist Tom Volk). First Im going to examine the amount of precipitation in the period of 10-14 days before each observation.

rain_when_fruiting <- filter(daily_data, t_minus > 6)
totals_by_day <- rain_when_fruiting %>%
  group_by(id) %>%
  summarise(total_precipitation = sum(precipitation_sum))

ggplot(totals_by_day) + geom_density(mapping=aes(total_precipitation),fill="red", alpha=.4) + geom_vline(aes(xintercept=median(total_precipitation)), color="blue", linetype="dashed")

I would have assumed that some precipitation was necessary just prior to fruiting, though this seems not to be the case. Almost 20% of the observations saw 5mm or less of rain in the area in the week prior to observation. A natural next step would be to compare average rainfall in the area of the observation to the total precipitation value, which could shed some light on whether above-average rainfall is a predictor of morel emergence.

count(totals_by_day[totals_by_day$total_precipitation <= 5, ]) / 200

Next, Ill examine humidity, air, and soil temperature data. First, Ill plot the hourly data for each observation on a layered plot, then Ill overlay the median temperature and quintile range (median chosen here instead of mean because there are some obvious outliers)

get_summary_stats <- function(dataset, x_axis, y_axis){
  x <- dataset %>%
    group_by({{x_axis}}) %>%
      summarise(median = median({{y_axis}}), q20=unname(quantile({{y_axis}},probs=0.20)), q80=unname(quantile({{y_axis}},probs=0.80)))
  return(x)
}

temp_stats <- get_summary_stats(dataset = hourly_data, x_axis = t_minus, y_axis = temperature_2m)
humidity_stats <- get_summary_stats(hourly_data, t_minus, relativehumidity_2m)
soil_stats <- get_summary_stats(hourly_data, t_minus, soil_temperature_0_to_7cm)
plot_all_observations <- function(dataset,x,y,group, xlab=NULL, ylab=NULL){
  return(ggplot(dataset, mapping=aes(x={{x}},y={{y}})) + geom_line(aes(group={{group}})) + scale_x_reverse() + xlab(xlab) + ylab(ylab) + theme(axis.text.x = element_blank()))
}


plot_summary_stats <- function(dataset,x, xlab, ylab){
  return(ggplot(dataset, aes(x={{x}}))+ geom_line(mapping=aes(y=median), color="black", linewidth=0.5) + geom_ribbon(mapping=aes(ymin=q20,ymax=q80), color='red', alpha=0.2, fill='red') + scale_x_reverse() + xlab(xlab) + ylab(ylab) + theme(axis.text.x = element_blank()))

}

plot_all_observations(hourly_data,t_minus,temperature_2m,id,"Time (14 days)","Temperature (C)") + labs(title="Temperatures by observation")

plot_summary_stats(temp_stats,t_minus,"Time (14 days)","Temperature (C)") + labs(title="Median temperature over time")

Plotting the middle 80% of the data, we find that morels can appear with daytime highs ranging from 10-20C (50-68F) and with lows as cold as 3C (37F) over the two weeks prior to the observation. The range of temperatures is wider than Id have thought. In particular, I was surprised to see how cold tolerant the mushrooms are. Ive always believed that morels are unlikely to emerge when temperatures fall below 40C

Well do the same for soil temperature and humidity, respectively.

plot_all_observations(hourly_data,t_minus,soil_temperature_0_to_7cm,id,"Time (14 days)","Soil Temperature (C)") + labs(title="Soil temperature by observation")

plot_summary_stats(soil_stats,t_minus, "Time (14 days)", "Soil Temperature (C)") + labs(title='Median soil temperature over time')

plot_all_observations(hourly_data,t_minus,relativehumidity_2m,id,"Time (14 days)","Relative Humidity (%)") + labs(title="Relative humidity by observation")

plot_summary_stats(humidity_stats,t_minus,"Time (14 days)", "Relative Humidity (%)") + labs(title="Median humidity over time")

Here again we have a similar story: a fairly wide range of weather conditions allow for morel appearance. Of all the parameters, humidity seems the most restrictive, with a peak humidity of 65 - 90% bounding most of the observations. It will come as news to nobody that mushrooms prefer moist areas, but knowing the lower end the the range could help identify areas in the drier Western states where it may be worth it to hunt for morels. For instance, Flagstaff, AZ has an peak March daytime humidity of 66% and indeed, morels have been document there. Phoenix, on the other hand (50% peak humidity in March, April and May), is probably hopeless.

While I dont think Ive made any earth-shattering findings about morel ecology, Im excited about how this relatively easy method of accessing historical weather data could be used to link historical weather data to any set of events. There are a lot of potential use cases here. To name a few:

  • Identifying the weather variables that most strongly predict emergency department admissions for asthma.
  • Creating a list of locations where rare species are most likely to be found
  • Predicting the volume of Christmas shopping based on December weather
